project: cvvdp CPU Path A — RECOVERED + RE-MEASURED (task #127 recovery)
date: 2026-05-29
host: lilith (AMD Ryzen 9 7950X 16-Core, 32 threads, 128 GB RAM, water-cooled)
os: Linux 6.6.114.1-microsoft-standard-WSL2

git_commit: eb925f13ea5b94f3fabb5694c5d8a722bf93b51b
  (recovered Path A tip 4cec7e70 = phase9zf path-a + parity-verify commit eb925f13;
   Path A merge-base with prior master = 5979e084; 16 Path-A commits recovered onto
   master after a push-race orphan lost them — see CHANGELOG.)
build_commit: eb925f13ea5b94f3fabb5694c5d8a722bf93b51b
binary: target/release/cpu-profile
driver: benchmarks/heaptrack/drivers/cpu_profile/src/main.rs
  run_cvvdp strip + warm_ref_strip arms construct via Cvvdp::new_strip(w,h,params,512)
  (Path A strip-major dispatcher), NOT the pool-only score_strip that produced the
  earlier peak==full canonical-table rows.

toolchain: rustc 1.95.0 (59807616e 2026-04-14) / cargo 1.95.0 (f2d3ce0bd 2026-03-21)
profile: workspace [profile.release] — opt-level=3, lto="thin", codegen-units=16,
         debug="line-tables-only". NO -C target-cpu=native (runtime archmage SIMD
         dispatch only). Global ~/.cargo only sets +simd128 (WASM, irrelevant on x86_64).
heaptrack: 1.3.0

machine_state: QUIET. Verified before the measurement run: no process > 30% CPU
  except claude daemons (~13%); zensim v02_372feat_sweep.py (the only heavy job
  earlier, ~29 threads) had finished; no fresh (<5 min) .workongoing markers besides
  this agent's own. Re-checked immediately before launching the wall block.

methodology:
- HEAP: PROCESS peak via `heaptrack target/release/cpu-profile cvvdp <mode> <W> <H>`,
  then `heaptrack_print <trace>.zst | grep "peak heap memory consumption"`.
  This is the heaptrack process peak (the only acceptable memory evidence per the
  global rule — NOT RSS-from-ps, NOT allocator-API bytes, NOT struct-size estimates).
  Heaptrack ran in a separate process from the wall runs (heaptrack adds overhead).
- WALL: score-only wall = the driver's `t_score_ms` (excludes the synth-image step),
  median of N=7 timed release runs per (mode,size), NO heaptrack attached. Spread is
  tight (16 MP full 4522–4664 ms; 30 MP full 8350–8582 ms), see wall_score_ms_all.
- NO EXTRAPOLATION: every heap and wall number is a real run at the stated dims.
  16 MP = 4096×4096, 30 MP = 6000×5000 (the canonical table's large size, exact dims).
- The driver auto-generates deterministic ref/dist; JOD score column confirms strip
  and full produce identical scores within each size (bit-identical, matching the
  270-cell strip_parity to_bits() gate that passed 6/6 on this same commit).

RESULTS (peak heap from heaptrack process peak, wall = median of 7 t_score_ms runs).
Full 6-size sweep (512^2, 1024^2, 2K, 12 MP, 16 MP, 30 MP) — the 16/30 MP block ran
first; 512^2..12 MP added 2026-05-29 same session, same quiet machine, same binary:

  size   mode            heap_GB   wall_ms   strip-vs-baseline (heap / wall)
  512^2  full            0.0559    59.11     baseline
  512^2  strip           0.0612    51.20     +9% / -13%   <- CROSSOVER: strip heap HIGHER
  512^2  warm_ref        0.0482    57.95     baseline
  512^2  warm_ref_strip  0.0607    50.99     +26% / -12%  <- CROSSOVER: strip heap HIGHER
  1024^2 full            0.2234    233.63    baseline
  1024^2 strip           0.1780    173.69    -20% / -26%  <- lower AND faster
  1024^2 warm_ref        0.1926    230.00    baseline
  1024^2 warm_ref_strip  0.1759    174.26    -9%  / -24%  <- lower AND faster
  2K     full            0.8931    958.00    baseline
  2K     strip           0.6047    688.22    -32% / -28%  <- lower AND faster
  2K     warm_ref        0.7702    964.78    baseline
  2K     warm_ref_strip  0.5965    688.98    -23% / -29%  <- lower AND faster
  12MP   full            2.6200    3011.06   baseline
  12MP   strip           1.3600    1840.81   -48% / -39%  <- lower AND faster
  12MP   warm_ref        2.2600    2839.00   baseline
  12MP   warm_ref_strip  1.3300    1838.90   -41% / -35%  <- lower AND faster
  16MP   full            3.660     4610.07   baseline
  16MP   strip           1.580     2603.53   -57% / -43%  <- lower AND faster
  16MP   warm_ref        3.150     4476.60   baseline
  16MP   warm_ref_strip  1.550     2621.70   -51% / -41%  <- lower AND faster
  30MP   full            6.540     8482.17   baseline
  30MP   strip           2.550     4550.69   -61% / -46%  <- lower AND faster
  30MP   warm_ref        5.640     7819.37   baseline
  30MP   warm_ref_strip  2.490     4599.24   -56% / -41%  <- lower AND faster

ACCEPTANCE GATE (task #127):
  strip peak heap < full peak heap  — MET at 16 MP (1.58 < 3.66) AND 30 MP (2.55 < 6.54)
  strip wall <= full wall           — MET at 16 MP (2604 <= 4610) AND 30 MP (4551 <= 8482)
  Gate met decisively at both required sizes.

CROSSOVER (measured, not assumed):
  At 512^2 the per-strip scratch pre-allocation (Scratch::new_strip persistent weber
  slots + per-strip band workspaces) costs MORE heap than full's monolithic buffers
  (strip 0.0612 GB > full 0.0559 GB; warm_ref_strip 0.0607 > warm_ref 0.0482). Strip is
  still WALL-faster at 512^2 (-13%). The heap crossover is gone by 1024^2 (strip -20%)
  and the advantage widens monotonically to 30 MP (-61%). So: strip is always >= as
  fast, and lower-memory for every size at/above ~1 MP. This matches the brief's
  expectation that "small sizes have per-strip overhead" — documented here, not hidden.

NOTE vs prior #127 claim (cpu_path_a_2026-05-28.meta, now superseded for wall):
- HEAP matches the prior claim almost exactly: strip 1.58 GB @16MP (claimed 1.58),
  warm_ref_strip 1.55 GB @16MP (claimed 1.55). Independently reproduced.
- WALL absolute numbers differ from the prior claim (prior: full 11.32 s, strip 6.04 s
  @16MP; this run: full 4.61 s, strip 2.60 s). The prior numbers were "median of 3
  runs" with no recorded machine-quiet state and likely a different timer (whole-process
  vs t_score_ms). The RELATIVE win (strip ~-43% @16MP) is consistent with the prior
  claim's -47%. Per the global no-extrapolation / re-measure rule, the numbers in THIS
  file are the authoritative ones; the prior file's wall column is treated as an
  unverified historical estimate.

raw heaptrack traces: NOT committed from this run (the prior chain's
  benchmarks/heaptrack/*.zst @16/40MP are the committed traces; this run's traces lived
  in /tmp/patha_ht.* and were consumed for the peak figures above). The peak_heap_bytes
  column IS the heaptrack-extracted process peak.

commands:
  cargo build --release -p cpu-profile
  BIN=target/release/cpu-profile \
    OUT_TSV=crates/cvvdp/benchmarks/cpu_path_a_recovered_2026-05-29.tsv \
    N_WALL=7 bash crates/cvvdp/benchmarks/measure_path_a.sh
  (harness committed at crates/cvvdp/benchmarks/measure_path_a.sh)
